\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator\'27s report indicates that criteria 1\'2C 2\'2C 5 and 7 need improvement and criteria 3\'2C4\'2C6 and 8 meet minimum standards. The main problem in this application is the design of the programme. All modules are pegged at level 7 so it is not clear how students are supposed to jump from level 4 to level 7 without any intermediary steps. The content of these modules at level 7 does not show the depth required for subjects at this level. In addition\'2C the application says that students can articulate with the B Com Honours at RBS. This cannot be as they do not have an Honours programme and actually students should be able to articulate with any Honours Accounting programme in the country.\line \line There is a further contradiction in that it is stated that the programme is offered by contact though in the submission RBS purports to be a distance institution. Incorrect CESM Classification of programme\'3A\line  The First Qualifier is  0401 Business Administration\'2C Management and Operations\line  The second qualifier is  040101 Business Administration and Management\'2C General\line  The CESM classification of the programme is wrong.  The first qualifier should be \'E2\'80\'9C0402 Accounting and related services\'E2\'80\'9D as the programme is designated as an Accounting degree. The second qualifier should be \'E2\'80\'9C040201 Accounting\'E2\'80\'9D. In the application the programme is often referred to as a programme related to the discipline of management\'2C for example\'3A\line \'E2\'80\'9CThe HEQC has prescribed minimum standards for a Bachelor\'27s degree. These standards require that the BCOM programme must contain all the functional areas of management.\'E2\'80\'9D  It is not clear whether this is a mistake\'2C or if the programme is geared more towards management\'2C in which case the 040101-classification would be correct.  Currently the inconsistencies make the application confusing. As a result it is currently impossible to assess if learning outcomes\'2C degree of curriculum choice\'2C teaching and learning methods\'2C modes of delivery and learning materials cater for the learning needs of its target student intake.  Competencies expected of students are currently not at the correct NQF-level\'2C see discussion below.  Currently all modules are designed to a NQF-level 7 standard.  This is incorrect as only 120 credits need to be at a NQF-level 7 and a maximum of 96 credits should be NQF-level 5. As the planning of the outcomes of the programme should have been based on the relevant NQF-levels\'2C the whole programme needs to be reconceptualised.\line \line  It is not clear if the budget is sufficient. A budget of R1 050 000 is allocated for the development of learning programmes.  As this seems to be the budget for the business school as a whole\'2C it is unclear how much is allocated to this particular programme and therefore it is impossible to assess if the budget for the development of learning materials is adequate. \line \line The institution has a Student Recruitment Selection And Admission Policy.This programme complies with the basic requirement for admission to a Bachelor\'E2\'80\'99s degree\'2C namely\'3A\line \'E2\'80\'9CDegrees\'3A NQF Exit level 7\line  The National Senior Certificate or equivalent\'E2\'80\'9D\line  In the Government gazette 26 November 2009 it is however stated that in addition\'2C a student must \'28a\'29 achieve at least 60\'25 in three fundamental subjects\'2C including the language of learning and teaching in the higher education institution\'2C \'28b\'29 achieve at least 70\'25 in four vocational  subjects\'2C chosen from the NC \'28V\'29 Level 4 subjects.\'E2\'80\'9D\line \line These additional requirements are not stated in the admission requirements. Regent Business School intends enrolling a maximum of 200 students for this programme with an approximate annual growth rate of 20\'25 thereafter. \line Enrolment Plan\'3A Head Count 3 year Projection \line Qualification  2012  2013  2014 \line BCom\'3AAcc   200   220    264\line The numbers envisaged are admirable when taking into account the need for accountants nationally.\line \line As indicated earlier in this report\'2C it is not clear how all these students will be accommodated in a lecture at any given time\'2C as the largest lecture hall can only accommodate 70 persons.  This could have an effect on the quality of education provided to the students. This relates to the teaching and learning hours table where 40\'25 of the time will be contact...if this is so\'2C then how this will be achieved must be clarified. \line \line Staffing appears to be adequate but if the programme is to achieve its outcomes there is the possibility of overloading of some lecturers. As indicated before in discussions of criteria one\'2C two and four above\'2C the mode of delivery is problematic. \line \line  In the application the mode of delivery is indicated as \'E2\'80\'9Ccontact\'E2\'80\'9D\'2C however in the institutional information in the application\'2C mention is made of \'E2\'80\'9Cthe flexible mode of delivery of the RBS programme \'28distance and supported learning\'29\'E2\'80\'9D.  It is also stated that the programme is geared towards \'E2\'80\'9Cespecially those in full time employment\'2C require\'28e\'29ing the opportunity to study at their own pace and time by flexible distance learning with minimal disruption to their working environments and lives.  It is therefore not entirely clear what the delivery mode is. No information is given on lectures\'2C only on workshops.  As indicated before the venues cannot accommodate the whole cohort of students who are envisaged in the enrolment plan.\line \line The model described by the institution is not one which is compliant with contact institutions and best describes the distance mode of delivery.  Other elements put in place to monitor progress of students and ensure appropriate support. \line The moderation process for assessments is not clear. The appointment of moderators\'2C their role and involvement in the marking process should be established.\line \line Security of marks- A clear segregation of duties in the capturing and administration of marks is not evident\'2C although it is stated that a security system does exist.\line \line It is difficult to assess the suitability of the infrastructure when the mode of delivery is unclear\line \line Based on the above comments by the evaluator\'2C the Directorate does not support the \'27provisional accreditation with condition\'27 of the programme and recommends \'27 non-accreditation\'27 \cell \pard 

